english:
  title: Record of the New School at Xiangyang
  author: An Chuk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The lands east of the passes possess wondrous and elegant waters. Within them lies Xiangyang, gathering the finest spirits and clearest essence of that region. Yet across more than a hundred years, I have heard of no gifted and virtuous scholar born from this county who might grace the annals of men. This is no fault of the mountain's spiritual power, nor the people's wicked nature—rather, this county has long bordered the frontier, where turmoil has repeatedly risen and the way of learning has been left untended.

    Now that the realm is unified and the people know no war, the Way of the Sages awakens anew and youth flourish daily. Surely we must establish a school to nurture talent. Yet those who govern this place make haste only with ledgers and records, their thoughts never reaching this aim. Thus the county's vital essence coils and stagnates, finding no outlet; the young remain bound and cannot break free. Is this not the people's great misfortune?

    When I arrived, the elders told me of a cave to the north, called the Cave of the Sage Duke. This must be the ancient seat of learning, long fallen to ruin. My heart sighed. I at once commanded the people to restore it. All rejoiced, saying, "This is our own desire"—such joy that labor was forgotten. I sent word to my former examination brother, Magistrate Chen of Tongzhou, to oversee the work. Soon Magistrate Park arrived to take his post—Park too, the son of that cultured gentleman Sangmun, used his own strength to fulfill my vision. Is this not the people's great fortune?

    When earth's vital force has long declined, its surge comes swift; when what is stored lies dormant long, its emergence blooms abundant. From this day forth, may each household nurture brilliant and learned descendants, and each village embody kindness and virtue. Then shall the shame of these mountains and waters be washed away, and you will know my words were not in vain. Though what we have built is rough and incomplete, with gaps remaining, I hope those wise ones who come after will cast their eye upon it.
  footnotes:
    - The Cave of the Sage Duke (文宣王洞) refers to a legendary site associated with Confucius, implying this was intended as a Confucian academy.
    - An Chuk's reference to 'mountain and waters' carries double meaning—both the literal geography and the spiritual essence believed to emerge from natural landscapes in classical Chinese thought.
    - The author emphasizes that the county's misfortune stems not from natural deficiency but from administrative neglect during years of frontier instability.
